ce in contemporary Welsh and Anglo-Saxon texts. This study reveals that the region of the Welsh borderlands was much more culturally coherent, and the impact of the Norman Conquest on it much greater, than has been previously realised.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aMedieval Studies 2020. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aAnglo-Saxon Chronicle.  aAnglo-Saxon law codes.  aAnglo/Welsh antagonism.  aBede.  aDunsaete Agreement.  aGuthlac of Crowland.  aHistoria Ecclesiastica.  aNorman conquest.  aOld English riddles.  aPenda of Mercia.  aWelsh Borderlands.  aagricultural labour.  aborderlands outlaw.  acattle theft.  adark Welsh.  amilitary culture.  aslaves.  avernacular literary tradition.1 aBrady, Lindy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packagez978311128281740uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152611574440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526115744423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526115744/original  a978-3-11-128281-7  Manchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packageb2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles